kernel_variant.solution:
\textbf{Preliminaries}  
Denote by  
\[
\Omega_{d}=\frac{2\pi^{d/2}}{\Gamma\!\bigl(\tfrac{d}{2}\bigr)}
\]  
the surface area of the unit $(d-1)$-sphere in $\mathbb R^{d}$.  
For a spherically symmetric mass distribution in $d$ dimensions the generalised shell theorem states

\begin{itemize}
\item[(i)] the mass $M(r)$ enclosed by the hypersphere of radius $r$ is  
\[
M(r)=\int_{0}^{r}\Omega_{d}\,s^{\,d-1}\rho(s)\,ds,
\]
\item[(ii)] a unit test mass situated at distance $r$ from the centre is attracted with force magnitude  
\[
F(r)=\frac{M(r)}{r^{\,d-1}} .
\tag{1}
\]
\end{itemize}

Hence  
\[
M(r)=r^{\,d-1}F(r),\qquad 
\frac{dM}{dr}=\Omega_{d}\,r^{\,d-1}\rho(r).
\tag{2}
\]

\bigskip
\textbf{Step 1.  Density $\rho(r)$ (task (a))}  

Insert the empirical force law \eqref{star} into \eqref{2}:

\[
M(r)=c\,r^{\,d-1}\,r^{\,d-1}\,e^{\beta r^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)^{p}
     =c\,r^{\,2d-2}\,e^{\beta r^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)^{p}.
\tag{3}
\]

Differentiate:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{dM}{dr}
&=c\,e^{\beta r^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)^{p}\,\frac{d}{dr}\bigl[r^{\,2d-2}\bigr] \\
&\quad +c\,r^{\,2d-2}\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)^{p}\,\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl[e^{\beta r^{2}}\bigr] \\
&\quad +c\,r^{\,2d-2}e^{\beta r^{2}}\,\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl[(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p}\bigr].
\end{aligned}
\]

The elementary derivatives are  

\[
\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl[r^{\,2d-2}\bigr]=(2d-2)r^{\,2d-3},\qquad
\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl[e^{\beta r^{2}}\bigr]=2\beta r\,e^{\beta r^{2}},\qquad
\frac{d}{dr}\!\bigl[(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p}\bigr]=2p\gamma r\,(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p-1}.
\]

Factorising $e^{\beta r^{2}}(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p-1}$ gives  

\[
\frac{dM}{dr}
=2c\,r^{\,2d-3}\,e^{\beta r^{2}}\,(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p-1}
\Bigl[(d-1)(1+\gamma r^{2})+\beta r^{2}(1+\gamma r^{2})+p\gamma r^{2}\Bigr].
\tag{4}
\]

Using the second relation in \eqref{2} we obtain

\[
\boxed{\;
\rho(r)=\frac{2c}{\Omega_{d}}\,r^{\,d-2}\,e^{\beta r^{2}}\,(1+\gamma r^{2})^{p-1}
\Bigl[(d-1)(1+\gamma r^{2})+\beta r^{2}(1+\gamma r^{2})+p\gamma r^{2}\Bigr]
\;}.
\tag{5}
\]

\bigskip
\textbf{Step 2.  Fixing $c$ from the prescribed total mass $M_{0}$ (task (b))}  

Because $M(r)$ is explicit, simply set $r=a$ in \eqref{3}:

\[
M_{0}=M(a)=c\,a^{\,2d-2}\,e^{\beta a^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma a^{2}\bigr)^{p},
\]

whence  

\[
\boxed{\; 
c=\dfrac{M_{0}}{a^{\,2d-2}\,e^{\beta a^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma a^{2}\bigr)^{p}}
\;}.
\tag{6}
\]

\emph{Consistency check.}  
Insert \eqref{5} into the definition of $M(r)$, switch to the variable $t=r^{2}$, and integrate:

\[
\begin{aligned}
M(a)&=\Omega_{d}\int_{0}^{a}r^{\,d-1}\rho(r)\,dr\\
    &=c\int_{0}^{a^{2}}\frac{d}{dt}\Bigl[t^{\,d-1}(1+\gamma t)^{p}e^{\beta t}\Bigr]\,dt\\
    &=c\,a^{\,2d-2}\,e^{\beta a^{2}}\bigl(1+\gamma a^{2}\bigr)^{p}=M_{0},
\end{aligned}
\]

which indeed reproduces \eqref{6}.

\bigskip
\textbf{Step 3.  Exterior field (task (c))}  

For $r\ge a$ the entire mass $M_{0}$ acts as though concentrated at the centre, hence by \eqref{1}

\[
\boxed{\;
F_{\text{out}}(r)=\dfrac{M_{0}}{r^{\,d-1}},\qquad r\ge a
\;}.
\tag{7}
\]

\bigskip
\textbf{Step 4.  Special case $d=4,\ \beta=0,\ p=2$ (task (d))}  

The surface area of the unit $3$-sphere is $\Omega_{4}=2\pi^{2}$.  
Insert $d=4,\ \beta=0,\ p=2$ into \eqref{5}:

\[
\begin{aligned}
\rho_{4}(r)
&=\frac{2c}{2\pi^{2}}\,r^{2}\,(1+\gamma r^{2})^{1}
\Bigl[3\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)+2\gamma r^{2}\Bigr]\\[2mm]
&=\frac{c}{\pi^{2}}\,r^{2}\bigl(1+\gamma r^{2}\bigr)\bigl(3+5\gamma r^{2}\bigr).
\end{aligned}
\tag{8}
\]

From \eqref{6} one finds

\[
\boxed{\;
c=\dfrac{M_{0}}{a^{6}\bigl(1+\gamma a^{2}\bigr)^{2}}
\;}.
\tag{9}
\]

Finally, with $d=4$, equation \eqref{7} gives the exterior force

\[
\boxed{\;
F_{\text{out}}(r)=\dfrac{M_{0}}{r^{3}},\qquad r\ge a
\;}.
\tag{10}
\]

All requested formulae have now been obtained.
